The port is a MODIFIED derivative: it is written from scratch in Node.js (Headroom's
live implementation is Rust), diverges deliberately from upstream (it spills dropped
array rows to a file referenced as `full=<path>` instead of Headroom's content-addressed
`<<ccr:HASH …>>` handle, and it uses a distinct-count uniqueness budget in place of
Headroom's SimHash + Kneedle `compute_optimal_k`), and adds fnd-specific pipeline stages
(ADF→markdown, noise drop, long-string truncation) that are not part of SmartCrusher.

The fixtures under tests/parity/fixtures/smart_crusher/ are copied verbatim from the
Headroom repository (tests/parity/fixtures/smart_crusher/, same Apache-2.0 license). They
are the porting contract: tests/json-slim-fixtures.mjs runs the port against them and
pins byte-parity (16/17) or, where JavaScript number semantics prevent it, value-parity
(1/17 — the time_series fixture, whose float-valued whole numbers `0.0` re-serialize to
`0`).

